32:11.746 --> 32:18.914
DeBakey's group. And what they sought was an 
ability during a surgical procedure,

32:18.934 --> 32:39.458
particularly a thoracic-type procedure where 
there was blood loss, whether in the old days,

32:18.934 --> 32:39.458
bypass surgery produced a lot more blood loss than 
it does today, but these aortic aneurysm

32:18.934 --> 32:39.458
procedures and all that, there's a high amount of 
blood loss. Two things were problematic even

32:40.180 --> 32:45.867
before the AIDS epidemic. One was that the 
availability of blood, the ability to transfuse

32:45.887 --> 32:54.197
enough blood to keep these patients alive. And 
number two, with donor transfused blood or

32:54.718 --> 33:10.137
homologous transfusion, which means the blood 
from someone else, there was clinically a fairly

32:54.718 --> 33:10.137
significant risk associated with non-A, non-B 
hepatitis. And even today, non-A, non-B,

33:10.842 --> 33:18.351
hepatitis is clinically much higher a risk factor 
than AIDS is. But nonetheless, the doctors were

33:18.912 --> 33:23.698
familiar with this risk way back. And so what Dr. 
DeBakey wanted was a better way to, and they had

33:24.639 --> 33:35.432
some more modest systems that would take a 
patient's blood during surgical procedure,

33:24.639 --> 33:35.432
recycle it, But it would do maybe one unit of blood 
every 20 minutes. Well, in one of these aneurysm

33:39.065 --> 33:46.498
patients, you might need to go through six or seven 
units of blood in 20 minutes. So making a long story

33:46.538 --> 34:02.584
short, they developed a system that would take the 
blood, it would run it through a filter, then it

33:46.538 --> 34:02.584
would run it through a centrifuge separating the 
red cells from the plasma and platelets, wash down

33:46.538 --> 34:02.584
those red cells and re-infuse those red cells, a 
unit of red cells to the patient. And it was capable

34:07.798 --> 34:11.161
of doing this in a matter of two or three minutes. So 
it meant that you could almost keep real time up.

34:15.305 --> 34:32.520
And that not only produced much less risk of a 
transfusion-related disease, but just in terms

34:15.305 --> 34:32.520
of blood, we had a patient in California after we 
